|population = 313,288<ref>[http://www.knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121153548/http://www.knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php |date=November 21, 2013 }}</ref>
|regions    = {{flagcountry|Kenya}}
|region1   = 
|languages  = 
|religions  = [[Traditional African religion|African Traditional Religion]], [[Islam]] 
|related    = [[Mijikenda peoples|Mijikenda]], other [[Bantu peoples]]
}}
The '''Digo''' are an ethnic and linguistic group based near the [[Indian Ocean]] coast between [[Mombasa]] in southern [[Kenya]] and [[Tanga, Tanzania|Tanga]] in northern [[Tanzania]]. In 1994 the Digo population was estimated to total 305,000, with 217,000 ethnic Digo living in Kenya and 88,000 (1987 estimate) in Tanzania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=dig |title=Chidigo |publisher=Ethnologue |date=1999-02-19 |accessdate=2015-11-13}}</ref> Digo people speak the [[Digo language]], called Chidigo by speakers, a [[Bantu language]]. They are part of the greater [[Mijikenda peoples|Mijikenda]] ethnic group of people which contains nine smaller groups or tribes, including the [[Duruma]], [[Giriama]], and others.

Digo women do a tremendous amount of labor, but are excluded from participating in politics, religion, kinship issues, and major economic transactions.

