{{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Luxembourg}} "Donne-moi une chance" | image = | caption = | year = 1993 | country = Luxembourg | artist = Simone Weis, Jimmy Martin | as = [[Modern Times (band)|Modern Times]] | with = | language = | languages = [[French language|French]], [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]] | composer = Patrick Hippert, Jimmy Martin | lyricist = Patrick Hippert, Jimmy Martin | conductor = Francis Goya | place = 20th | points = 11 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1993lu from Diggiloo Thrush] | prev = Sou fräi | prev_link = Sou fräi | next = | next_link = | next_year = }} '''"Donne-moi une chance"''' ([[English language|English]] translation: "Give me a chance") was the [[Luxembourg]]ish entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993]], performed in [[French language|French]] and [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]] by the duo [[Modern Times (band)|Modern Times]]. The song was the third ever [[Luxembourg in the Eurovision Song Contest|Luxembourgish entry]] to feature lyrics in the Luxembourgish language, in this case however only partly.
The song is an up-tempo, [[rock music|rock]]-influenced number, with the vocalists pleading with each other to ''"Give me a chance to tell you"'' about how they feel while on a romantic date. Modern Times also recorded the song in English, as "Heaven Only Knows".
The song was performed fifteenth on the night (following [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]'s [[Niamh Kavanagh]] with "[[In Your Eyes (Niamh Kavanagh song)|In Your Eyes]]" and preceding [[Slovenia]]'s [[1X Band]] with "[[Tih deževen dan]]"). At the close of voting, it had received 11 points, placing 20th in a field of 25.<ref name="Big in Eurovision"/>
The song remains the last Luxembourgish representative at the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], as after the 1993 Contest Luxembourg opted to stop competing.<ref name="Big in Eurovision">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/top-10-entries-from-luxembourg|title=Luxembourg: Small in size, big in Eurovision|author=Victor Escudero|date=19 November 2017|publisher=Eurovision TV|accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref>
