{{Infobox building |name = Le Mirabeau |image = Le Mirabeau.jpg |location = 1, Avenue Princesse Grace, Monte-Carlo, Monaco |coordinates = |status = Complete |start_date = |completion_date = 1973 |building_type = |architectural_style = Modernist |roof = |floor_count = 26 |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = |architect = |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = [[Caroli Group]] |owner = [[David and Frederick Barclay]] |management = |references = }} '''Le Mirabeau''' is a high-rise building in [[Monaco]]. Formerly a luxury hotel, it is now a residential building.
==Location== It is located at number 1 on the [[Avenue Princesse Grace]] in [[Monte-Carlo]], Monaco.<ref name="emporismirabeau">[http://www.emporis.com/building/le-mirabeau-monaco-monaco Le Mirabeau], [[Emporis]]</ref><ref name="jbpastoretfils">[http://jbpastoretfils.mc/?chantier=le-mirabeau&lang=en J.B. Pastor & Fils Monaco: RÉSIDENCE LE MIRABEAU]</ref>
==History== It was built by the [[Caroli Group]] with concrete in the [[modernist architecture|modernist]] architectural style in 1973.<ref name="emporismirabeau"/><ref name="groupecaroli">[http://caroli-realestate.com/fr/presentation Groupe Caroli: Presentation]</ref> It is eighty-one metres high, with twenty-six storeys.<ref name="emporismirabeau"/> It is the tenth-tallest building in Monaco.<ref>[http://www.emporis.com/statistics/tallest-buildings-monaco Monaco's tallest buildings - Top 20], Emporis</ref>
It was formerly a luxury hotel managed by [[Société des bains de mer de Monaco]] (SBM).<ref name="emporismirabeau"/><ref name="montecarlosbm">[http://www.montecarlosbm.com/resort-en-2/history/ Monte-Carlo SBM: History]</ref> The owners were [[David and Frederick Barclay]], through their holding company called Ellerman Investments.<ref name="dailytelegraph">Richard Fletcher, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2869120/Barclay-brothers-hit-by-2.2m-loss-at-the-Ritz.html Barclay brothers hit by £2.2m loss at the Ritz], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', November 16, 2003</ref><ref>Paul Murphy, Jon Henley, [https://www.theguardian.com/business/1999/dec/04/9 A police state for the rich], ''[[The Guardian]]'', December 4, 1999</ref><ref>Simon Clark, Erik Schatzker, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aITPndZplKNo Britain's Billionaire Barclay Twins Use Stealth to Amass Empire], ''Bloomberg'', November 29, 2004</ref> It was home to ''La Coupole'', a restaurant run by chef Didier Aniès which received one star in the [[Michelin Guide]].<ref name="montecarlosbm"/> In 2004, the building was renovated by architects [[Ivan Brico]] and [[Ange Pecoraro]].<ref name="montecarlosbm"/> In December 2007, the hotel closed down.<ref name="emporismirabeau"/> In May 2008, 1,000 SBM employees stopped outside the former hotel during their demonstration to express their discontent at their allegedly poor working conditions.<ref>[http://www.nicematin.com/article/menton/monaco-manifestation-pres-de-1-000-salaries-dans-la-rue-hier.53196.html Monaco Manifestation : près de 1 000 salariés dans la rue hier], ''[[Nice-Matin]]'', May 08, 2008</ref>
It was renovated by the construction firm [[J.B. Pastor & Fils]] from 2007 to 2010, and turned into a residential building.<ref name="jbpastoretfils"/> A [[green wall]] was added.<ref>[http://www.greenplus.com/index.php?mact=Actu,m77609,detail,1&m77609actu_id=6&m77609returnid=46&page=46 Green Plus: Mur végétal Résidence le Mirabeau 350 m2 à Monaco]</ref>
The ''Club des Résidents Etrangers de Monaco'' (CREM) is headquartered in this building.<ref>[http://www.club-residents-etrangers-monaco.com/en/contact.html Club des Résidents Etrangers de Monaco: Contact]</ref>
